a new routine that still signals the workday is   over and now I can unwind. The cue and the reward\nneed to stay the same but the behavior changes. And   that's the key, it's not just about stopping the \nhabit, it's about rerouting it in a way that still   feels satisfying for your brain. Now let's go a \nlittle deeper because behind every behavior is an   identity and this brings us to the identity trap. \nMany of us have self-concepts built around our   habits, we say things like "I'm a night owl" "I'm an \nemotional eater," "I'm terrible with routines." These   identity statements feel like honest descriptions \nof yourself but they're more than that. They're   prescriptions for future behavior. When \nyou label yourself as someone who always   procrastinates, you're unconsciously giving \nyourself permission to keep procrastinating,  your brain works to maintain consistency between \nyour actions and your self-image so what can you   do instead? You reframe the identity and update \nyour self-concept. Instead of saying, "I'm a night   owl," try "I've gotten used to staying up late \nbut I'm learning how to protect my sleep."   Instead of "I have no self-control," try "I'm \npracticing better decision-making in the moment."   It's a subtle shift but it matters because \nwhen you change your identity narrative, your   behavior begins to align with that new story. \nIf you want to do deeper work on your narrative   identity, take a look at my workbook called Unlock \nYour Story Digital Workbook, it can help you   identify some of the stories that you tell \nyourself and understand how you view the world. It's a digital download that you get immediately \nand not a physical book. I'll have it linked to   this video. Another major factor keeping bad \nhabits alive is cognitive distortions. Those   sneaky thought patterns that justify continuing \nthe behavior that you're trying to stop. One of the   most common is the "Just this once" rationalization.\nYour brain is incredibly persuasive when it wants   something convincing you that one exception won't \nmatter in the grand scheme of things but here's   what's happening on a neural level. Each time you \nmake an exception, you're actually reinforcing the   habit loop rather than breaking it. You're telling \nyour brain that the rule isn't absolute, making it   easier to make exceptions again in the future. "All \nor nothing thinking" is another distortion that   sabotages habit change. When you slip up once and \nthink "Well I've ruined my streak so I might as   well just give up completely." You're falling \nprey to perfectionism, your brain likes clear   categories but real habit change is rarely \na perfect linear process. Then there's "false   permission giving," creating believable excuses \nto indulge. "I had a hard day so I deserve this,"    or "I'll start fresh on Monday," "Everyone else \nis doing it," these thoughts feel reasonable in   the moment but they're just your brain's way of \ngetting what it wants. Learning to recognize these   thinking patterns gives you power over them, When \nyou catch yourself saying, "just this once," pause   and ask "Is this thought helping me become who \nI want to be?" This creates space between the   urge and the action allowing your prefrontal \ncortex to engage before your automatic habit takes   over. Now, let's move from theory to practice. I'm \ngoing to give you five sciencebacked strategies   to help you rewire your brain and give you a \nbetter chance at long-term habit change. Number   one, Environmental design. Make the habit harder \nto do, add friction, want to stop doom scrolling, delete the app, or log out, so it takes longer to \naccess. Want to cut back on snacking, store treats   in a cabinet that's harder to reach. Even small \nchanges like these can interrupt the automatic   loop. Next is implementation intentions, these are \nspecific if then plans for handling habit triggers. If I feel stressed, then I'll take