13	13	Have you ever had one of those mornings where everything just feels a little off? You're groggy. You can't focus. And it feels like your brain isn't even online yet. Most of us have. But here's the thing, that mental fog isn't just random. It's often the result of how you start your day. I'm Dr. Tracy Marx, a psychiatrist, and I make mental health education videos to help you strengthen your mind, fortify your brain, and build resilience. And in this video, we're looking at how your morning routine can literally shape the rest of your day mentally, emotionally, and neurologically. Now, I want to be clear upront. This isn't about becoming a 5 a.m. cold plunge person. And you don't need a 2-hour morning ritual with green juice and journaling under a Himalayan sunrise. What I'm going to share are five simple elements of a morning routine that supports your brain's natural chemistry and helps you operate from your most resilient self. So, let's start with why mornings matter so much. Your brain doesn't wake up all at once. There's a natural sequence of events that kicks in and one of the main drivers of that sequence is cortisol. Cortisol gets a bad rap because it's considered the stress hormone, but it's also your get upandgo hormone. Under normal circumstances, your cortisol levels spike within the first 30 to 45 minutes after you wake up. And this is called the cortisol awakening response. It's what helps you feel alert, motivated, and ready to take on your day. But here's the catch. That natural rhythm can be disrupted by poor sleep, stress, inconsistent routines, and even checking your phone before you're out of bed. And when your cortisol rhythm is off, you may feel groggy in the morning and wired at night, which is the exact opposite of what your brain needs to be resilient. So, what can you do to work with your brain's natural rhythm? Let me give you five sciencebacked elements of a morning routine that help unlock your best mental state. The first one is light exposure. Your brain needs light to know when it's time to be awake. Sunlight, especially within the first hour of waking, helps suppress melatonin, the hormone that makes you sleepy and reinforces your circadian rhythm. Think of it like flipping on your brain's internal switch. Ideally, go outside for 5 to 10 minutes. But if that's not possible, open the blinds and sit by a window. Even if it's cloudy, outdoor light is far more powerful than indoor bulbs. And if you wake up before the sun comes up, a light therapy box can be a helpful alternative. Second thing, gentle movement. And I'm not talking about a full workout. Just moving your body, stretching, walking, doing a few yoga poses. These activities boost blood flow to your brain and trigger the release of dopamine and norepinephrine which improve alertness and focus. Movement also engages your prefrontal cortex, the part of your brain that helps with planning, decision making, and emotional regulation. In other words, it gives you a head start on focus and calm. Third, mental priming. This is where you decide what kind of mindset you're going to bring into your day. Your brain is especially impressionable right after waking up. So those first thoughts really matter. And you can do this through journaling, setting an intention, or just silently repeating a phrase like, "Today I will respond instead of react." Even a 30-se secondond intention can steer your brain away from chaos and into clarity. To set an intention, you don't have to create a detailed to-do list or put pressure on yourself. Instead, you can choose one primary intention. And this might be focusing on what you can control, approaching challenges with curiosity instead of stress, or simply deciding to respond thoughtfully rather than react impulsively. This practice takes less than a minute, but it shifts your brain from reactive mode to intentional mode. So instead of just responding to whatever happens, you have a guiding principle that helps you make better decisions and stay aligned with your values. If you want help with this part, my essential tools card deck includes grounding and intention setting cards that are perfect for morning use. You can grab a card, take one breath, and give your brain a direction for the day. Fourth, hydration. Your brain is about 73% water and doesn't store water overnight. Even mild hydration, 1 to 2%, can impair memory, concentration, and mood. So before your coffee or breakfast, drink a full glass of water. If plain water doesn't appeal to you, add a splash of lemon or a pinch of sea salt. This one habit alone can help reduce brain fog and stabilize your mood throughout the morning. And finally, one tiny win. This could be as small as making your bed, watering your plants, or writing down your top tasks for the day. When you complete even one small task, your brain gets a little hit of dopamine. That chemical that signals progress and reward. That burst of dopamine is like a mental ignition. It creates momentum, and momentum builds motivation. The key here isn't to do all five things perfectly every morning. It's to choose one or two that fit in your life and make them consistent because consistency is what builds new neural pathways. And that's where we loop back to neuroplasticity, the brain's ability to change and grow based on what you do repeatedly. When you prime your brain every morning with just a few minutes of structure, light, movement, hydration, or intention, you're actually rewiring the way your brain handles stress and focus. And these five practices activate your prefrontal cortex, calm your nervous system, and help restore your natural rhythm. It's not just a feel-good routine. It's a neurological reset that improves your brain's resilience over time. And remember, these are not rigid rules. You don't have to do all five in a specific order or for a set amount of time. Think of them as tools. Use the ones that serve you and leave room for flexibility. Let me give you an example of what this can look like in real life. You wake up and before grabbing for your phone, you take three deep breaths. You open the blinds or step outside for 2 minutes of sunlight. While sipping your water, you say one sentence. Today, I will focus on what I can control. That's it. You've already done more for your brain than most people will do all morning. And it doesn't have to be perfect to be powerful. And if you're wondering how to bring the same kind of intentionality to the end of your day, stay tuned for the next video. I'll walk you through a simple evening windown process that helps your brain release the day and prepare for deep, restorative rest. In the meantime, I'd love to hear from you in the comments. What's one thing you already do in the morning that helps you feel grounded or focused? Or if mornings are a struggle, what's one habit that you'd like to try after watching this video? And if you want help building your own morning ritual, you can find my essential tools card deck at mental wellnesspace.store. It includes prompts, breathing exercises, grounding tools, and mindset cues designed to help you start your day on purpose. Thanks for spending your time today with me. I'm Dr. Tracy Marx, and I'll see you in the next video.	en	2026-05-03 11:00:03.495645
